1.ddPCR

Kate Bowie, PhD and Lisa Karstens, PhD

2025-02-28

Purpose

How much microbial DNA is there in blood (quantity)?

* looking at each fraction (copies of 16S by ddPCR)
* intracellular vs extracellular? (DNase)
* is there varying amounts of DNA in each fraction? are they statistically different in the fractions of blood?
* any association with disease?

Notes:

  • adjusted copies - samples normalized by input volume to ddpcr
  • final copies - samples normalized by input vol to ddpcr, ALSO by elution volume
  • adjusted_tot_blood - samples normalized by total blood volume extracted

Fractions

ddpcr$fraction <- factor(ddpcr$fraction, levels = c("plasma", "RBC", "BF", "WB", "mock_community", "water"))

ddpcr_means <- ddpcr %>% 
  filter(dnase == "no" & !(fraction %in% c("water", "mock_community")) & !patient_ID == "neg") %>%
  mutate(fraction = droplevels(fraction)) %>%
  group_by(fraction,patient_ID ) %>%
  summarise(mean_copies = mean(adjusted_tot_blood)) %>%
  ungroup()
  
ddpcr_fried <- friedman_test(mean_copies ~ fraction | patient_ID, data = ddpcr_means )
plot_means <- ddpcr_means %>% 
  ggplot(., aes(x = fraction, y = mean_copies)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_bw() +
  ylim(0, 650) +
  ylab("Copies of 16S rRNA gene") + xlab("Blood Fraction") + 
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("plasma" = "Plasma", "RBC" = "RBC", "BF" = "BF", "WB" = "WB")) 

stat.test <- compare_means(mean_copies ~ fraction, data = ddpcr_means,  method = "wilcox.test", p.adjust.method = "fdr")

stat.test <- ddpcr_means %>%
  pairwise_wilcox_test(
    mean_copies ~ fraction,
    p.adjust.method = "fdr") %>%
  ungroup()

Fig1a_means <- plot_means + stat_pvalue_manual(stat.test, label = "p.adj.signif", y.position = c(200, 275, 350, 425, 500, 575))

DNase vs Non-DNase

Evaluate each fraction’s dnased and non-dnased samples.

ddpcr_means_dnase <- ddpcr %>% 
  filter(!(fraction %in% c("water", "mock_community")) & !patient_ID == "neg") %>%
  mutate(fraction = droplevels(fraction)) %>%
  group_by(fraction,dnase, patient_ID ) %>%
  summarise(mean_copies = mean(adjusted_tot_blood)) %>%
  ungroup() 

plot <- ddpcr_means_dnase %>% 
  ggplot(., aes(x = dnase, y = mean_copies)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank()) +
  facet_wrap(~fraction, scales = "free_x", nrow = 1) +
  ylab("Copies of 16S rRNA gene") + xlab("Blood Fractions with and without DNase") + guides(fill=guide_legend(title=""))

stat.test <- ddpcr_means_dnase %>%
  group_by(fraction) %>%
  pairwise_wilcox_test(
    mean_copies ~ dnase,
    p.adjust.method = "fdr") %>%
  ungroup()

stat.test <- stat.test %>% add_xy_position(x = "dnase")

Fig1b_means <- plot + stat_pvalue_manual(stat.test, y.position = c(400,400,400,400), label = "p.adj.signif")

Significant differences between all fractions and their dnase-counterparts execpt for Buffy coat (BF). This indicates that there is cell-free DNA. Also plasma is a good check for this, as the dnased plasma sample has almost 0 copies, which is expected.

Disease Associations

Adding Disease

ddpcr_means_dx <- ddpcr_means_dnase %>% 
mutate(disease = case_when(
patient_ID %in% c(1,8,10,14,15) ~ "low-grade",
patient_ID %in% c(4,5,9,11,12) ~ "high-grade",
patient_ID %in% c(2,3,6,13,16) ~ "screen-negative",
TRUE ~ patient_ID,
))

Overall

ddpcr_means_dx$disease <- factor(ddpcr_means_dx$disease, levels = c("screen-negative", "low-grade", "high-grade"))

# overall
plot <- ddpcr_means_dx %>% 
  filter(dnase == "no") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = disease, y = mean_copies, fill = disease)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("screen-negative" = "Screen Negative", 
                              "low-grade" = "Low Grade", 
                              "high-grade" = "High Grade")) +
  labs(y = "Mean Copies", x = "Disease")  # Capitalized axis labels


my_comparisons <- list(c("screen-negative", "low-grade"), c("screen-negative", "high-grade"), c("low-grade", "high-grade"))

plot + stat_compare_means(comparisons = my_comparisons, label.y = c(1050, 1150, 1300), method = 'wilcox.test', tip.length = 0.01, label = "p.adj")

# seeing any assoc. with dnase
plot <- ddpcr_means_dx %>% 
  filter(dnase == "yes") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = disease, y = mean_copies, fill = disease)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("screen-negative" = "Screen Negative", 
                              "low-grade" = "Low Grade", 
                              "high-grade" = "High Grade")) +
  labs(y = "Mean Copies", x = "Disease")


my_comparisons <- list(c("screen-negative", "low-grade"), c("screen-negative", "high-grade"), c("low-grade", "high-grade"))

plot + stat_compare_means(comparisons = my_comparisons, method = 'wilcox.test', label = "p.adj")

# overall comparing high vs low vs healthy
ddpcr_means_dx %>% 
  filter(dnase == "no" ) %>%
  kruskal.test(mean_copies ~ disease, data = .)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  mean_copies by disease
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 0.015738, df = 2, p-value = 0.9922
ddpcr_means_dx %>% 
  filter(dnase == "yes" & !(fraction %in% c("water", "mock_community"))) %>%
  kruskal.test(mean_copies ~ disease, data = .)

##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
##
